{"source_key":"sha256-a93d5e12b74542ffeb860fd5a6e2a70f","record_index":22,"record_hash":"sha256:aab8e7cbe87844452e018057c7b675144b599c0353c97a97ef248bd5bd983cb6","timestamp":"2026-06-03T08:48:14.372Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Wall time: 3.4379 seconds\nOutput:\n{\"pull_request\":{\"url\":\"https://github.[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"number\":13854,\"state\":\"closed\",\"merged\":true,\"mergeable\":false,\"draft\":false,\"body\":\"Resolves issue mentioned in https://github.[REDACTED:entropy].\\r\\n\\r\\nThe original issue is that Ubuntu 26.04 LTS now has a new default terminal emulator, `ptyxis`, superseding `gnome-terminal`. I've added support for `ptyxis` in general in a separate PR (https://github.[REDACTED:entropy]), but it still means that new users from 26.04 won't have \\\"open in termal\\\" working out-of-the-box.\\r\\n\\r\\nSo basic options were to either switch to ptyxis now or somehow detect Ubuntu 25.10+, when it was added. Both have significant downsides - there are still a lot of users on 24.04 and other distros and hardcoding logic seems fragile.\\r\\n\\r\\nAs a general solution, I thought we can just consider all supported terminals, when trying to figure what's to use as the default for the current user.\\r\\nSo I moved `defaultTerminalForPlatform` from frontend to backend so we can run `which` on all terminals we do support and subsequnetly `allTerminalOptions` now also comes from Rust. Tested - works fine, no errors.\\r\\nOne special case in `get_recommended_terminal_for_platform` - we don't check anything using `which` and just use `terminal`, as it's generally available on every Mac and is the system default there.\\r\\n\",\"title\":\"feat: auto-detect installed user default terminal\",\"base\":\"master\",\"base_sha\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"head\":\"autodetect-terminal\",\"head_sha\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"merge_commit_sha\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"user\":{\"login\":\"A